Anthropic's Model Context Protocol includes a critical remote code execution vulnerability - newly discovered exploit puts 200,000 AI servers at risk


Security researchers at OX Security have uncovered a critical remote code execution vulnerability in Anthropic's Model Context Protocol (MCP), affecting its official SDKs in Python, TypeScript, Java, and Rust. The issue stems from insecure STDIO handling, where unsanitized user input is directly executed, impacting up to 200,000 server instances and over 150 million downloads. Despite the severity, Anthropic declined to patch the flaw, considering it “expected behavior.” MCP, an open standard enabling AI model integration with external tools, was donated to the Linux Foundation but remains maintained by Anthropic. Major platforms including OpenAI and Google have adopted it. OX identified four major exploitation vectors, including UI injection, prompt injection in IDEs, bypasses in hardened tools, and supply chain poisoning. They successfully infiltrated 9 of 11 MCP registries, executing code on six live systems. At least 10 critical CVEs have been issued, with only some patched. The researchers urged protocol-level fixes, such as command whitelisting, but Anthropic declined. This vulnerability disclosure follows a recent source code leak from Anthropic and raises questions about the company’s internal security practices, especially after launching Claude Mythos, a new AI model touted for its security testing capabilities.

