Anthropic launches tool to connect AI systems directly to datasets


Anthropic has introduced a new open-source tool called the Model Context Protocol (MCP) that enables AI assistants to directly connect to various data sources, enhancing their information retrieval and task execution capabilities. This universal protocol aims to simplify integration across different AI systems and data, addressing the current need for custom coding for each dataset. The MCP allows developers to integrate once and connect seamlessly to multiple data sources. For example, using the Claude desktop app, Anthropic demonstrated how MCP could connect directly to GitHub, create a new repository, and make a pull request in under an hour. Companies like Replit, Codeium, and Souregraph have already adopted MCP for their AI agents. MCP aims to address fragmented integrations by providing a standardized protocol that maintains context as AI systems interact with different tools and datasets, fostering a more sustainable architecture for future AI developments.

Windows is getting support for the 'USB-C of AI apps'


Microsoft is advancing its AI integration in Windows by supporting the Model Context Protocol (MCP), dubbed the "USB-C of AI apps," and launching the Windows AI Foundry. MCP, introduced by Anthropic, allows AI apps to connect seamlessly with other software, services, and Windows components. This move is part of Microsoft’s vision for a Windows environment where AI agents play a central, interactive role. MCP servers will access core Windows features like the file system and Subsystem for Linux, creating more intuitive, automated functions within apps. For example, Perplexity can use MCP to search user documents via natural language rather than manual folder navigation. To ensure secure implementation, Microsoft is initially releasing MCP support to selected developers. Security measures include a controlled MCP registry, user consent prompts, and adherence to strict guidelines to prevent issues like token theft and prompt injections. Microsoft is also rebranding its AI infrastructure under the Windows AI Foundry, integrating with tools like Foundry Local, Ollama, and Nvidia NIMs, thereby simplifying AI model deployment. The company is collaborating with hardware partners such as AMD, Intel, Nvidia, and Qualcomm to support this ecosystem. Overall, Microsoft aims to balance innovation with robust security and user experience.

AI companies want a new internet - and they think they've found the key


Over the past 18 months, major AI companies including OpenAI, Google, Microsoft, and Anthropic have coalesced around a new standard called MCP (Model Context Protocol), aimed at enabling AI agents to access tools, apps, and data over the internet in a consistent and standardized manner. Initially built as a side project by Anthropic engineers, MCP has rapidly become the de facto industry standard, allowing AI agents to interact more effectively with services—much like APIs enabled the explosive growth of Web 2.0. Anthropic has now donated MCP to the Linux Foundation and joined forces with other key players to form the Agentic AI Foundation (AAIF) to promote open-source development in agentic AI. MCP’s success lies in its ability to simplify integration between AI models and digital services, enhancing speed, reliability, and automation. It allows AIs like Claude to "converse" with tools like Slack more efficiently—streamlining complex tasks into seamless agent interactions. Its future, however, remains uncertain amidst wider adoption, competition, and the need for strong security standards. Nevertheless, the shift toward open collaboration and more transparent protocols marks a pivotal moment in building a more functional, AI-driven internet.

