'This is not a traditional coding error': Experts flag potentially critical security issues at the heart of Anthropic's MCP, exposes 150 million downloads and thousands of servers to complete takeover


Security researchers from Ox have uncovered a critical and systemic vulnerability in Anthropic's Model Context Protocol (MCP), a core AI system used for securely connecting models to external data sources and applications. The flaw reportedly affects every SDK implementation of MCP—in Python, TypeScript, Java, and Rust—placing over 150 million downloads, 200,000 instances, and more than 7,000 publicly accessible servers at risk of remote code execution (RCE). Unlike typical coding errors, this vulnerability stems from architectural design choices in the MCP protocol. The issue allows attacks ranging from prompt injections in AI IDEs to unauthorized UI manipulations and malicious marketplaces exploits. Major platforms such as LiteLLM, LangChain, and IBM’s LangFlow are impacted. Despite Ox having issued 10 CVEs and assisting with bug fixes, they emphasize that the core problem in the protocol remains unresolved. While Ox recommended permanent patches, Anthropic responded that MCP is functioning as intended. The flaw's widespread use across leading AI tools, including products from OpenAI, DeepMind, and Anthropic's own Claude apps, raises significant industry-wide security concerns.

Anthropic's official Git MCP server had some worrying security flaws - this is what happened next


In January 2026, Anthropic resolved multiple critical security flaws in its Git Model Context Protocol (MCP) server, a tool enabling AI systems to interact with Git repositories. Discovered by the security startup Cyata, the vulnerabilities—CVE-2025-68145 (path validation bypass), CVE-2025-68143 (unrestricted git_init), and CVE-2025-68144 (argument injection in git_diff)—could be chained with the Filesystem MCP server to achieve remote code execution (RCE) or file tampering via prompt injection. Cyata emphasized the risk of combining seemingly secure components in agentic AI systems, warning that complex integrations may produce unforeseen security gaps. Although the issues were reported in June 2025, Anthropic released a fix in December 2025 (version 2025.12.18). No exploitation in the wild has been reported. The news follows recent disclosures that Claude, Anthropic’s AI, had been involved in a sophisticated cyber espionage campaign, further underlining the emerging security challenges in AI-enabled environments, especially as businesses rapidly integrate such technologies.

