AI agents using Anthropic MCP could be a vector for supply chain attacks, claim researchers


Researchers at OX Security have uncovered a critical vulnerability in Anthropic's Model Context Protocol (MCP), a widely adopted AI agent communication standard. This flaw allows arbitrary command execution on servers using vulnerable MCP implementations, posing serious supply chain security risks. The issue enabled researchers to access multiple active services of real companies and conduct over 30 responsible disclosures, resulting in 10 Critical/High CVEs and numerous patches. The vulnerability stems from a GPT Researcher function allowing user-supplied OS commands to be executed via a custom STDIO MCP server configuration—regardless of server startup status. While initially thought to be a flaw in LangChain's MCP adapter, the root of the problem was traced back to Anthropic’s official MCP SDK. Anthropic responded by asserting the behavior was intentional and required user consent, later issuing a security advisory urging caution in usage. However, OX Security criticized this approach, warning that shifting responsibility to developers—who may lack security expertise—exposes users and organizations to substantial risk. Experts warn that this illustrates deeper systemic issues in rapidly expanding AI ecosystems where security often lags functionality, and untested standards can enable large-scale cyberattacks.

Anthropic reveals Claude Opus 4.6, an enterprise-focused model with 1 million token context window for extended code capabilities


Anthropic has introduced Claude Opus 4.6, a significant upgrade of its enterprise-focused AI model, designed for complex knowledge work and agentic coding tasks. A central feature is its one million token context window, allowing it to process entire codebases and handle long, detailed tasks more effectively. The model achieves notable benchmarks, including 65.4% on Terminal-Bench 2.0 and 1,606 on GDPval-AA Elo, outpacing competitors like GPT-5.2 and Gemini 3 Pro. Claude Opus 4.6 also introduces ‘Agent Teams,’ enabling multiple AI agents to collaborate, along with new API features such as ‘adaptive thinking’ and context compaction for long conversations. The model shows advances in knowledge retrieval, especially in legal and financial contexts, and integrates directly with Microsoft 365 apps like Excel and PowerPoint. Customer testimonials highlight its proficiency in tasks such as codebase migration, legal analysis, and autonomous IT issue management. Despite its enhanced capabilities, Claude Opus 4.6 remains priced at $5 per million input tokens and $25 per million output tokens.

Anthropic says MCP will stay 'open, neutral, and community-driven' after donating project to Linux Foundation


Anthropic and OpenAI are donating major AI projects to the Linux Foundation to support the launch of the Agentic AI Foundation (AAIF), a new initiative aimed at fostering open, community-driven innovation in agentic AI. The AAIF, backed by key tech players like AWS, Cloudflare, Google, Block, and Bloomberg, is positioned as a neutral platform to develop tools, standards, and ecosystem support for collaborative AI development. Anthropic is contributing its Model Context Protocol (MCP), originally open-sourced in 2024, to ensure it remains "open, neutral, and community-driven." MCP has become the standard for integrating AI models with external tools and enterprise infrastructure, supporting projects across major platforms such as Claude, Microsoft Copilot, Gemini, and ChatGPT. With over 10,000 MCP servers running globally, it has become a cornerstone of AI integration. OpenAI is also contributing its AGENTS.md format, a universal standard to guide and coordinate AI coding agents. Widely adopted by over 60,000 projects, AGENTS.md enhances reliability and interoperability of agent behavior across repositories. This move reflects OpenAI's commitment to fostering transparency, safety, and shared governance in the AI agent ecosystem.

