OpenAI, Anthropic, and Block Are Teaming Up to Make AI Agents Play Nice


OpenAI, Anthropic, and Block have co-founded the Agentic AI Foundation (AAIF) to establish open standards for AI agents, promoting interoperability and collaboration in the emerging agentic AI space. Under the Linux Foundation's governance, they have donated key technologies: Anthropic’s Model Context Protocol (MCP), OpenAI’s Agents.md, and Block’s Goose framework. These tools, already free to use, will now be developed openly by the community. The AAIF has also gained support from major tech firms like Google, Microsoft, AWS, Bloomberg, and Cloudflare. The move marks a shift from traditional chatbot interfaces toward AI agents that can perform web-based tasks, collaborate, and negotiate. OpenAI's Srinivas Narayanan views open standards as essential for seamless interaction between AI systems, while Block sees widespread developer interest in contributing to Goose’s development. This initiative reflects broader challenges and trends in the AI industry, where the use of open-source tools could influence global AI adoption and potentially give strategic advantages. With parallels to open web standards, the AAIF aims to shape the far-reaching impact of AI agent infrastructure in a transparent and stable manner.

